                                                                  2837 1451
  This evaluation provides a complete representation of the       2837 1451
nuclear data needed for transport, damage, heating,               2837 1451
radioactivity, and shielding applications over the incident       2837 1451
neutron energy range from 1.0E-11 to 150 MeV.  The discussion     2837 1451
here is divided into the region below and above 20 MeV.           2837 1451
                                                                  2837 1451
INCIDENT NEUTRON ENERGIES < 20 MeV                                2837 1451
                                                                  2837 1451
  Below 20 MeV the evaluation is based completely on the ENDF/B-  2837 1451
VI (MOD3) evaluation by Larson, C. Perey, Hetrick, and            2837 1451
Fu.                                                               2837 1451
                                                                  2837 1451
INCIDENT NEUTRON ENERGIES > 20 MeV                                2837 1451
                                                                  2837 1451
  The ENDF/B-VI Release 2 evaluation extends to 20 MeV and        2837 1451
includes cross sections and energy-angle data for all             2837 1451
significant reactions.  The present evaluation utilizes a more    2837 1451
compact composite reaction spectrum representation above 20 MeV   2837 1451
in order to reduce the length of the file. No essential data for  2837 1451
applications is lost with this representation.                    2837 1451
  The evaluation above 20 MeV utilizes MF=6, MT=5 to represent    2837 1451
all reaction data.  Production cross sections and emission        2837 1451
spectra are given for neutrons, protons, deuterons, tritons,      2837 1451
alpha particles, gamma rays, and all residual nuclides produced   2837 1451
(A>5) in the reaction chains. To summarize, the ENDF sections     2837 1451
with non-zero data above En = 20 MeV are:                         2837 1451
                                                                  2837 1451
  MF=3 MT=  1  Total Cross Section                                2837 1451
       MT=  2  Elastic Scattering Cross Section                   2837 1451
       MT=  3  Nonelastic Cross Section                           2837 1451
       MT=  5  Sum of Binary (n,n') and (n,x) Reactions           2837 1451
                                                                  2837 1451
  MF=4 MT=  2  Elastic Angular Distributions                      2837 1451
                                                                  2837 1451
  MF=6 MT=  5  Production Cross Sections and Energy-Angle         2837 1451
               Distributions for Emission Neutrons, Protons,      2837 1451
               Deuterons, Tritons, and Alphas; and Angle-         2837 1451
               Integrated Spectra for Gamma Rays and Residual     2837 1451
               Nuclei That Are Stable Against Particle Emission   2837 1451
                                                                  2837 1451
  The evaluation is based on nuclear model calculations that      2837 1451
have been benchmarked to experimental data, especially for n +    2837 1451
Ni58 and p + Ni58 reactions [Ch97]. We use the GNASH code system  2837 1451
[Yo92], which utilizes Hauser-Feshbach statistical,               2837 1451
preequilibrium and direct-reaction theories. Spherical optical    2837 1451
model calculations are used to obtain particle transmission       2837 1451
coefficients for the Hauser-Feshbach calculations, as well as     2837 1451
for the elastic neutron angular distributions.                    2837 1451
  Cross sections and spectra for producing individual residual    2837 1451
nuclei are included for reactions. The energy-angle-correlations  2837 1451
for all outgoing particles are based on Kalbach systematics       2837 1451
[Ka88].                                                           2837 1451
  A model was developed to calculate the energy distributions of  2837 1451
all recoil nuclei in the GNASH calculations [Ch96]. The recoil    2837 1451
energy distributions are represented in the laboratory system in  2837 1451
MT=5, MF=6, and are given as isotropic in the lab system. All     2837 1451
other data in MT=5,MF=6 are given in the center-of-mass system.   2837 1451
This method of representation utilizes the LCT=3 option approved  2837 1451
at the November, 1996, CSEWG meeting.                             2837 1451
  Preequilibrium corrections were performed in the course of the  2837 1451
GNASH calculations using the exciton model of Kalbach [Ka77,      2837 1451
Ka85], validated by comparison with calculations using Feshbach,  2837 1451
Kerman, Koonin (FKK) theory [Ch93].  Discrete level data from     2837 1451
nuclear data sheets were matched to continuum level densities     2837 1451
using the formulation of Gilbert and Cameron [Gi65] and pairing   2837 1451
and shell parameters from the Cook [Co67] analysis. Neutron and   2837 1451
charged- particle transmission coefficients were obtained from    2837 1451
the optical potentials, as discussed below.  Gamma-ray            2837 1451
transmission coefficients were calculated using the Kopecky-Uhl   2837 1451
model [Ko90].                                                     2837 1451
                                                                  2837 1451
SOME Ni-SPECIFIC INFORMATION CONCERNING THE EVAL.                 2837 1451
                                                                  2837 1451
  The neutron total cross section was evaluated based on the      2837 1451
least-squares method with GMA code system [Po81] taking account of2837 1451
the experimental data [Ci68, Pe73, Sc73, La83, Di97, Fa66, Du67]. 2837 1451
The data for natural Ni were also used because there was not      2837 1451
enough data for Ni-62 above 20 MeV. The data for natural Ni were  2837 1451
transformed to the Ni-62 cross section according to A*(2/3) law.  2837 1451
In the GMA analysis, the systematic error was assumed to be 1 %   2837 1451
for all the data set.  Result of the GMA evaluation was used as   2837 1451
the evaluated total cross section data above 20 MeV.              2837 1451
                                                                  2837 1451
The evaluated total cross section data (1 to 250 MeV) and s-wave  2837 1451
strength function [Mu81] were used to obtain the neutron optical  2837 1451
potential parameters. The parameter estimation was carried out    2837 1451
based on Marquart-Bayesian approach [Sm91], where ECIS95 code was 2837 1451
used for the optical model calculation.  We have employed the     2837 1451
energy dependence of the optical potential similar to Delaroche's 2837 1451
work [De89]. The initial potential parameters were adopted from   2837 1451
Koning and Delaroche [Ko97].  Total of 7 parameters concerning the2837 1451
central potential depth were estimated with associated covariance 2837 1451
matrix, while the geometrical parameters were fixed to the result 2837 1451
of a similar search for n + Ni-58. Presently obtained potential   2837 1451
was used for the calculation of neutron transmission coefficients 2837 1451
and DWBA cross sections in the energy region above 20 MeV.  Below 2837 1451
20 MeV, the Harper neutron potential [Ha82] was used for the      2837 1451
calculation of transmission coefficients.                         2837 1451
                                                                  2837 1451
The proton optical potential was also searched for to obtain a    2837 1451
good description of proton-total reaction cross section as        2837 1451
predicted by Wellisch-Axen systematic [We96] above 50 MeV.  The   2837 1451
parameter estimation was carried out by the Marquart-Bayesian     2837 1451
approach similar to the neutron OMP, but trying to seek the best  2837 1451
parameter to reproduce the reaction cross sections compiled by    2837 1451
Carlson [Ca96] and Wellisch values. The experimental data in      2837 1451
Carlson [Ca96] was scaled for Ni-62 according to A**(2/3) law.  In2837 1451
this search, the geometrical parameters were fixed to be same as  2837 1451
the neutron potential.  The present potential gives a good        2837 1451
description of the proton total reaction cross section from 10 MeV2837 1451
to 250 MeV.  However, after some trial and error to reproduce both2837 1451
the elastic scattering and reaction cross section data for Ni-58, 2837 1451
we have employed the following combination of proton potentials:  2837 1451
                                                                  2837 1451
 0 to   5 MeV  :  Harper potential [Ha82]                         2837 1451
 6 to  47 MeV  :  Koning and Delaroche [Ko97]                     2837 1451
48 to 260 MeV  :  Present OMP                                     2837 1451
                                                                  2837 1451
For deuterons, the Lohr-Haeberli [Lo74] global potential was used;2837 1451
for alpha particles the McFadden-Satchler [Mc66] potential was    2837 1451
used; and for tritons the Becchetti-Greenlees [Be71] potential was2837 1451
used.  The He-3 channel was ignored.                              2837 1451
                                                                  2837 1451
The direct collective inelastic scattering to the following levels2837 1451
in Ni-62 was considered by the DWBA-mode calculation of ECIS95:   2837 1451
                                                                  2837 1451
Jpi Ex(MeV) Deformation length                                    2837 1451
